# Checkdown (Demo)

## Introduction

The main goal of this package to create checking fields and boxes in `rmarkdown` or `quarto`. It can be used in class when teacher share materials and tasks (as an `.html` page or an `.html` slides), so student can solve some problems and check their work. It is really important since some students are too shy to ask a question, so you can create tasks that will check on the fly the understanding of the class material and give some hints to those students that get stuck. In contrast to the [`learnr`](https://rstudio.github.io/learnr/index.html) package the `checkdown` package works serverlessly without `shiny` and could be stored as a simple `.html` page (e. g. on Github Pages). In contrast to the [`exams`](https://www.r-exams.org/) output the `checkdown` package creates interactive auto-grading tasks. The interactive version of the [`exams`](https://www.r-exams.org/) output is bind to Blackboard Learn, that is really nice, but looks like an overkill for the simple task that `checkdown` solves.

Load the library:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(checkdown)
```
:::


## Ask question with the `check_question()` function

Imagine that we want to create a checkbox with the answer 4. All you need is to create a following chunk in your `rmarkdown` document:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_question(answer = 4)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

```{=html}
<form name="form_21018" onsubmit="return validate_form_21018()" method="post">
<input type="text" placeholder="" name="answer_21018"/>
<input type="submit" value="check"/>
<div id="result_21018"></div>
</form>
<script>function validate_form_21018() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_21018']['answer_21018'].value;if (x == '4'){text = 'Correct';} else {text = 'I have a different answer';} document.getElementById('result_21018').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){
         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');
         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1;res1 = document.getElementById('result_21018').innerText == 'Correct';text = res1;element.innerHTML = text;
         return false;
         }}</script>
```

:::
:::


It is possible to change wrong and right answer's messages using `wrong` and `right` arguments of the `check_question()` function. Let's create some more questions.

Solve 3+3:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_question(answer = 6, right = "correct", wrong = "not correct")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

```{=html}
<form name="form_18815" onsubmit="return validate_form_18815()" method="post">
<input type="text" placeholder="" name="answer_18815"/>
<input type="submit" value="check"/>
<div id="result_18815"></div>
</form>
<script>function validate_form_18815() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_18815']['answer_18815'].value;if (x == '6'){text = 'correct';} else {text = 'not correct';} document.getElementById('result_18815').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){
         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');
         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2;res1 = document.getElementById('result_21018').innerText == 'Correct'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_18815').innerText == 'correct';text = res1 + res2;element.innerHTML = text;
         return false;
         }}</script>
```

:::
:::


Type *la-la*:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_question(answer = "la-la")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

```{=html}
<form name="form_96701" onsubmit="return validate_form_96701()" method="post">
<input type="text" placeholder="" name="answer_96701"/>
<input type="submit" value="check"/>
<div id="result_96701"></div>
</form>
<script>function validate_form_96701() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_96701']['answer_96701'].value;if (x == 'la-la'){text = 'Correct';} else {text = 'I have a different answer';} document.getElementById('result_96701').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){
         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');
         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3;res1 = document.getElementById('result_21018').innerText == 'Correct'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_18815').innerText == 'correct'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_96701').innerText == 'Correct';text = res1 + res2 + res3;element.innerHTML = text;
         return false;
         }}</script>
```

:::
:::


It is possible to use `placeholder` argument in order to show what kind of answer you expect:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_question(answer = "la-la", placeholder = "ta-ta-ta")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

```{=html}
<form name="form_15526" onsubmit="return validate_form_15526()" method="post">
<input type="text" placeholder="ta-ta-ta" name="answer_15526"/>
<input type="submit" value="check"/>
<div id="result_15526"></div>
</form>
<script>function validate_form_15526() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_15526']['answer_15526'].value;if (x == 'la-la'){text = 'Correct';} else {text = 'I have a different answer';} document.getElementById('result_15526').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){
         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');
         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3, res4;res1 = document.getElementById('result_21018').innerText == 'Correct'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_18815').innerText == 'correct'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_96701').innerText == 'Correct'; res4 = document.getElementById('result_15526').innerText == 'Correct';text = res1 + res2 + res3 + res4;element.innerHTML = text;
         return false;
         }}</script>
```

:::
:::


Number of answers is not limited:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_question(answer = 1:5)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

```{=html}
